
Public Domain

A public domain is a domain name that is accessible over the internet by anyone.

Examples:

google.com
github.com
yourapp.com
Internet
   |
   +--> google.com
   +--> github.com
   +--> yourapp.com

Characteristics:

Reachable from anywhere on the internet.
Has a public DNS record.
Uses a public IP address.
Typically secured with HTTPS.

Example:

https://chat.example.com

Anyone can open it in their browser.



Private Domain

A private domain is only accessible within a private network (office, company, home lab, Kubernetes cluster, etc.).

Examples:

keycloak.local
company.internal
chat-service.local

or

http://192.168.1.10
http://10.0.0.5

These are not accessible from the public internet.

Example network:

Office Network

Laptop
   |
Router
   |
-------------------------
|                       |
keycloak.internal   db.internal

Someone outside the office cannot access these addresses.



| Feature                  | Public Domain  | Private Domain                                    |
| ------------------------ | -------------- | ------------------------------------------------- |
| Accessible from internet | ✅ Yes          | ❌ No                                              |
| DNS                      | Public DNS     | Internal DNS or hosts file                        |
| IP Address               | Public IP      | Private IP (192.168.x.x, 10.x.x.x, 172.16–31.x.x) |
| Used for                 | Websites, APIs | Internal services                                 |
| Example                  | `example.com`  | `keycloak.internal`                               |





| Feature                   | Localhost   | Private Network                                |
| ------------------------- | ----------- | ---------------------------------------------- |
| Visible to same machine   | ✅ Yes       | ✅ Yes                                          |
| Visible to other machines | ❌ No        | ✅ Yes (if they're in the same private network) |
| Internet can access       | ❌ No        | ❌ No                                           |
| Example                   | `127.0.0.1` | `10.0.0.5`, `192.168.1.20`, Docker network     |
